A: You can use PrintWriter's write method to write to the file.
Here is how you can modify your code:
```java
PrintWriter outputFile = new PrintWriter(OUTPUT_FILE);

while (inputFile.hasNext()) {
    numberOfNumbers++;
    oneNumber = inputFile.nextDouble();
    sum += oneNumber;
    runningTotal += oneNumber;
    average = sum / numberOfNumbers;

    outputFile.write(oneNumber + "\t" + runningTotal + "\n");

    System.out.printf("%-10.2f\t %.2f\n", oneNumber, runningTotal);
}

outputFile.close();
inputFile.close();
```

In this code, `outputFile.write(oneNumber + "\t" + runningTotal + "\n");` writes the number and running total to the output file. The "\t" is a tab character that separates the two values, and the "\n" is a newline character that starts a new line for each number.

Remember to close the PrintWriter after you're done writing to the file to ensure all data is written to the file.

Also, don't forget to close the Scanner after you're done reading from the file.

This should solve your problem.

